http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Essentials of Computer Programming Curriculum Framework

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Essentials of Computer Programming is a course for students with no formal computer programming experience. Students will spend the majority of time coding to solve real-world problems in a collaborative environment. The course focuses on developing computational thinking, refining problem-solving skills, and applying key programming concepts. Throughout the course, students will use developmentally appropriate and accurate terminology when communicating about technology. Essentials of Computer Programming does not require additional Arkansas Department of Education approval.
Computational Thinking
Students will use relevant program design and problem-solving strategies.
Discuss approaches to problem solving used in programming
Represent problem-solving logic
Interpret logical expressions using Boolean operators
Demonstrate operator precedence in expressions

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: (e.g., inside-out, left-to-right, order of operations, right-to-left)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Identify the appropriate use of control flow constructs
Demonstrate how large problems can be deconstructed into a sequence of smaller problems
Analyze and implement collaborative methods in problem solving when appropriate
Students will evaluate different data representations for storing information.
Classify the types of information that can be stored as variables

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: (e.g., integers, floating points, characters, Booleans, strings)

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Compare and contrast how variables of different data types are represented in computer memory
Compare techniques for manipulating and using data
Analyze data organizational structures
Students will create and evaluate algorithms to solve problems.
Define the term algorithm as used in programming
Apply algorithmic reasoning to connect problem-solving processes to programming
Investigate ways in which a sequence of algorithms can be combined to create new algorithms
Compare and contrast the functional characteristics

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., clarity, efficiency, understandability) of algorithms that solve the same problem

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Develop a procedure to test an algorithm
Validate the effectiveness of an algorithm in solving a defined problem
Computing Practice and Programming
Students will evaluate the use of programming languages to solve problems.
Compare and contrast computer programming paradigms and languages

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., machine code, object oriented languages, procedural languages, visual programming languages

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the sequence of steps necessary to create and execute a program on a computer
Manually trace the execution path of code to understand flow of control
Manually trace the execution path of code to determine the output for a sample input
Students will analyze the capabilities of a programming language.
Explain how variables are created and initialized
Explain how arrays/lists are created and initialized
Compare and contrast capabilities of a language for conditional branching
Compare and contrast capabilities of a language for iteration
Investigate various capabilities of a language for abstraction including functions, parameters, and return values
Recognize potential problems or limitations with conditional branching, iteration, and abstraction features

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., infinite loops, range checking on parameters, unreachable branches

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyze traditional programming algorithms
Examine methods used for the input and output of data
Students will create, test, and use computer programs to solve problems.
Design source code that is efficient and easy to read
Integrate clear and appropriate documentation within student designed source code
Use an editor or visual interface to create and execute programs

Implement computing applications by integrating software development tools and techniques
  • variables of different data types
  • arrays/lists of different sizes
  • conditional branching
  • iteration
  • combinations of conditional branching and iteration
  • functions (e.g., input/output libraries, graphical display libraries, math function libraries, user-defined functions)
Ensure program correctness by utilizing debugging output statements and test cases
Compare and contrast the implementation of two or more programming solutions for the same problem
Elements of Computing
Students will classify different types of computers and systems.
Identify a variety of electronic devices (e.g., computers, Global Positioning Systems [GPS], smart devices, vehicles) that contain computational processors and execute programs
Discuss current trends (e.g., improved user interaction, increasing processor speed and data storage, parallel and distributed systems) in computing
Students will describe the major components of a computer system.
Describe the hardware components of a computer
Identify unique components (e.g., accelerometers, GPS, touch screens) in mobile computing devices
Identify the main software components (e.g., operating system, programming tools, user applications) in a computer
Students will analyze the relationships within systems and components.
Demonstrate an understanding of the relationship of input and output among systems and components
Apply strategies to solve routine hardware problems
Evaluate tools (e.g., compilers, computer networks, interpreters, operating systems, program editors) necessary to support program execution
Social and Ethical Aspects of Programming
Students will analyze ethical and unethical uses of technology and programming.
Differentiate among open source, freeware, and proprietary software licenses
Discuss consequences of misuse of information and technology
Discuss social and economic implications (e.g., local, national, global) associated with ethical and unethical hacking and software piracy
Demonstrate legal and ethical behaviors when using information and technology
Apply academic integrity in programming
